Experimentation is needed for each set of items. Supervise the machine constantly when experimenting.</li><li class=\"ql-indent-1\">If there is not enough water in the machine, it will run out of liquid water and overheat (error E3).<strong> </strong><u>Immediately unplug the machine</u> and let it cool on its own (or follow the instructions and vent steam, then let everything cool). Overheating can easily damage or ruin the machine.</li><li class=\"ql-indent-1\">If there is too much water, the packs will come out wet (as opposed to damp) even if machine is vented and emptied as soon as the cycle finishes.</li><li>For the same reason, it can be very important that items also be loaded <em>in the same arrangement</em> every time. For example, if a pack containing cloth surgical drapes is loaded on the bottom next to the water, it may wick water up into itself when it is loaded or when the water starts to boil. This depletes the pool of liquid water and can result in overheating. But if a pack containing a metal box of instruments is loaded on the bottom, with the cloth drape pack on top, the problem can be avoided.</li></ul>","wtMeatHrs":0,"wtMilkHrs":0,"instructions":{"considerations":"<p>This SOP requires ~15 minutes of attention initially and ~50 minutes overall. Preferably, the machine should be vented and opened as soon as the cycle finishes; otherwise the packs will be wetter when they come out.</p>","restrictions":"<p>Only do this SOP if you have been specifically trained for it. There is a risk of severe burns (from hot items and from steam) if not performed properly.</p>","dothis":"<ul><li>Move the machine away from a wall and any overhanging cabinets etc. that may be damaged by steam. Leave it unplugged.</li><li><span style=\"background-color: rgb(255, 255, 0);\">Measure</span> exactly <strong>[one and three-quarters cups]</strong> of water into the bottom of the machine (if running multiple cycles in a row, carefully pour off the leftover water from the last cycle, then measure in the new water.)</li><li><span style=\"background-color: rgb(255, 255, 0);\">Load</span> the items to be autoclaved - first the metal grating, then <strong>[the instrument pack, then the towel pack, and then any individual instruments etc. on top]</strong>.</li><li><span style=\"background-color: rgb(255, 255, 0);\">Look at and feel the rubber gasket</span> on the inside of the machine's lid. Make sure that it is smooth and seated evenly, flush against the metal, all the way around with no wrinkles</li><li>Set the lid on the machine in the \"unlocked\" position. Rotate the lid back and forth to ensure that it is <span style=\"background-color: rgb(255, 255, 0);\">seated properly.</span></li><li>Rotate the lid to the \"<span style=\"background-color: rgb(255, 255, 0);\">locked</span>\" position and listen for a loud metallic \"click\". You will still be able to unlock this lid by turning it; that's ok, just make sure it's turned all the way counterclockwise and you hear a click.</li><li>Check that the regulator knob (weighted dial on the lid with \"pressure\" and \"steam\" printed on it) is in the \"<span style=\"background-color: rgb(255, 255, 0);\">Pressure</span>\" position.</li><li>Plug in the machine and press the \"<span style=\"background-color: rgb(255, 255, 0);\">Meat</span>\" button.</li><li><span style=\"background-color: rgb(255, 255, 0);\">Watch</span> the machine. The \"heating\" light should turn on, and the timer should show 35 minutes. Within 5-10 minutes, the \"heating\" light should turn off, the timer should start counting down, and the pressure display should turn on and show up to ~12 PSI. No more than a few gentle wisps of steam should be escaping. When the machine reaches this state, it is <u>safe to leave the room (but stay nearby)</u>.</li><li class=\"ql-indent-1\">If more than a tiny amount of steam escapes, the lid and/or gasket may not be seated properly - or you may not have the regulator set properly to \"Pressure\".</li></ul><p><br></p><ul><li>When the timer finishes, press the \"<span style=\"background-color: rgb(255, 255, 0);\">Off</span>\" button and let the machine sit for about 2 minutes <strong>[if packs are coming out soaking wet, experiment with this. Leaving them in lets some steam condense onto the packs, but venting steam too quickly makes the remaining water boil and splash up]</strong>.</li><li>Lay out a thick <span style=\"background-color: rgb(255, 255, 0);\">towel</span> next to the machine.</li><li>Put on long, heatproof, water resistant <span style=\"background-color: rgb(255, 255, 0);\">gloves</span>, or use a long-handled implement, and stand back from the machine and <span style=\"background-color: rgb(250, 204, 204);\">CAREFULLY and gently </span>turn the regulator to \"Steam\".</li><li class=\"ql-indent-1\">**This may allow hot steam to escape, going up to 2 feet straight up!**</li><li class=\"ql-indent-1\">It's best to let steam off as gently as possible. If it seems like there's a lot of steam, try letting the machine cool for another minute or two and trying again.</li><li>When the pressure display reads <span style=\"background-color: rgb(255, 255, 0);\">&lt;4 PSI, unplug</span> the machine.</li><li class=\"ql-indent-1\">do NOT attempt to remove the lid if the pressure is higher than this</li><li>With the heatproof gloves on, rotate the lid to the \"unlocked\" position.</li><li><strong><u>CAREFULLY, standing back as much as possible, lift the lid straight up until it is just free of the machine + rotate the near side of the lid downwards so the cloud of steam coming out of the machine is directed away from you and so that hot water on the inside of the lid drops into the machine.</u></strong></li><li>When the steam has dispersed, set the lid down on the towel to avoid dripping on the packs more than necessary</li><li>With the gloves on, carefully reach into the hot machine, <span style=\"background-color: rgb(255, 255, 0);\">remove</span> the packs, and set them on cooling racks to dry.</li><li class=\"ql-indent-1\">if the packs don't have enough heat to dry on their own, they can be dried in a 200-degree oven for 10-20 minutes.</li></ul><p><br></p><ul><li>If autoclaving multiple sets of items, the SOP can be restarted immediately - just remember to remove any remaining water and measure in new water.</li></ul><p><br></p><p><img src=\"https://cdn.filestackcontent.com/rPsfBxu6SPGjMZbThUDn\" style=\"display: block; margin: auto;\" width=\"929\"></p>","recordthis":"","success":"<p>The PSI readout should reach 12 PSI. (This indicates that it has gotten hot enough - it doesn't necessarily mean that it was at high enough pressure for long enough.)</p><p>You should not have any burns.</p>","failure":"<p><strong>[Inform [manager] and] </strong>consult the manual for troubleshooting advice if pressure does not reach 12 PSI and does not remain 9-12 PSI, or if autoclave tape doesn't darken.</p><p><br></p><h1><strong style=\"background-color: rgb(240, 102, 102);\"><em><u>In case of a burn:</u></em></strong></h1><ul><li>If skin is reddened or painful (it may turn white when pressed, but the color returns):</li><li class=\"ql-indent-1\">Remove any hot clothing or jewelry</li><li class=\"ql-indent-1\">Soak the affected area in cool (not cold) water for 15 minutes, while elevating it above the heart if possible</li><li class=\"ql-indent-1\">Consider anti-inflammatory / pain medication</li><li class=\"ql-indent-1\">Consider a clean dressing and petroleum-based ointment, but do not apply other topical treatments</li><li class=\"ql-indent-1\">Consider contacting emergency services if the burn is larger than the palm of the patient's hand; if it affects the face, a joint, or another sensitive area; or if the patient is a child, senior, or has another relevant medical condition</li><li class=\"ql-indent-1\">Avoid bursting any blisters that form</li><li>If skin has persistent white, brown, or black discoloration, or seems leathery or charred, or is <u>not </u>painful:</li><li class=\"ql-indent-1\">Contact emergency services immediately</li><li class=\"ql-indent-1\">Do not remove stuck-on clothing</li></ul>","references":"<p>Source for burn management: https://www.mayoclinic.org/first-aid/first-aid-burns/basics/art-20056649</p><p>Protocol originally written by Emma Ehrlich DVM. Supervise the machine constantly when experimenting.</li><li class=\"ql-indent-1\">If there is not enough water in the machine, it will run out of liquid water and overheat (error E3).<strong> </strong><u>Immediately unplug the machine</u> and let it cool on its own (or follow the instructions and vent steam, then let everything cool). Overheating can easily damage or ruin the machine.</li><li class=\"ql-indent-1\">If there is too much water, the packs will come out wet (as opposed to damp) even if machine is vented and emptied as soon as the cycle finishes.</li><li>For the same reason, it can be very important that items also be loaded <em>in the same arrangement</em> every time. If it seems like there's a lot of steam, try letting the machine cool for another minute or two and trying again.</li><li>When the pressure display reads <span style=\"background-color: rgb(255, 255, 0);\">&lt;4 PSI, unplug</span> the machine.</li><li class=\"ql-indent-1\">do NOT attempt to remove the lid if the pressure is higher than this</li><li>With the heatproof gloves on, rotate the lid to the \"unlocked\" position.</li><li><strong><u>CAREFULLY, standing back as much as possible, lift the lid straight up until it is just free of the machine + rotate the near side of the lid downwards so the cloud of steam coming out of the machine is directed away from you and so that hot water on the inside of the lid drops into the machine.</u></strong></li><li>When the steam has dispersed, set the lid down on the towel to avoid dripping on the packs more than necessary</li><li>With the gloves on, carefully reach into the hot machine, <span style=\"background-color: rgb(255, 255, 0);\">remove</span> the packs, and set them on cooling racks to dry.</li><li class=\"ql-indent-1\">if the packs don't have enough heat to dry on their own, they can be dried in a 200-degree oven for 10-20 minutes.</li></ul><p><br></p><ul><li>If autoclaving multiple sets of items, the SOP can be restarted immediately - just remember to remove any remaining water and measure in new water.</li></ul><p><br></p><p><img src=\"https://cdn.filestackcontent.com/rPsfBxu6SPGjMZbThUDn\" style=\"display: block; margin: auto;\" width=\"929\"></p>","recordthis":"","success":"<p>The PSI readout should reach 12 PSI. (This indicates that it has gotten hot enough - it doesn't necessarily mean that it was at high enough pressure for long enough.)</p><p>You should not have any burns.</p>","failure":"<p><strong>[Inform [manager] and] </strong>consult the manual for troubleshooting advice if pressure does not reach 12 PSI and does not remain 9-12 PSI, or if autoclave tape doesn't darken.</p><p><br></p><h1><strong style=\"background-color: rgb(240, 102, 102);\"><em><u>In case of a burn:</u></em></strong></h1><ul><li>If skin is reddened or painful (it may turn white when pressed, but the color returns):</li><li class=\"ql-indent-1\">Remove any hot clothing or jewelry</li><li class=\"ql-indent-1\">Soak the affected area in cool (not cold) water for 15 minutes, while elevating it above the heart if possible</li><li class=\"ql-indent-1\">Consider anti-inflammatory / pain medication</li><li class=\"ql-indent-1\">Consider a clean dressing and petroleum-based ointment, but do not apply other topical treatments</li><li class=\"ql-indent-1\">Consider contacting emergency services if the burn is larger than the palm of the patient's hand; if it affects the face, a joint, or another sensitive area; or if the patient is a child, senior, or has another relevant medical condition</li><li class=\"ql-indent-1\">Avoid bursting any blisters that form</li><li>If skin has persistent white, brown, or black discoloration, or seems leathery or charred, or is <u>not </u>painful:</li><li class=\"ql-indent-1\">Contact emergency services immediately</li><li class=\"ql-indent-1\">Do not remove stuck-on clothing</li></ul>","references":"<p>Source for burn management: https://www.mayoclinic.org/first-aid/first-aid-burns/basics/art-20056649</p><p>Protocol originally written by Emma Ehrlich DVM. USE</B></P>\n<P CLASS=\"Body\"><B CLASS=\"Bold\">SPECTRAMAST</B><SUP CLASS=\"SUPERScriptBold\">&reg;</SUP><B CLASS=\"Bold\"> LC</B> (ceftiofur intramammary suspension) Sterile Suspension is indicated for use in lactating dairy cattle for (1)&nbsp;the treatment of clinical mastitis associated with coagulase-negative staphylococci, <EM CLASS=\"Italics\">Streptococcus dysgalactiae, </EM>and <EM CLASS=\"Italics\">Escherichia coli</EM> and (2)&nbsp;the treatment of diagnosed subclinical mastitis associated with coagulase-negative staphylococci and <EM CLASS=\"Italics\">Streptococcus dysgalactiae</EM>.</P>\n<P CLASS=\"Label\"><B CLASS=\"Bold\">DOSAGE</B></P>\n<P CLASS=\"Body\">Infuse one (1) syringe into each affected quarter. Repeat this treatment in 24&nbsp;hours. For extended duration therapy, once daily treatment may be repeated for up to 8&nbsp;consecutive days.</P>\n<P CLASS=\"Label\"><B CLASS=\"Bold\">DIRECTIONS FOR USING THE PLASTET</B><SUP CLASS=\"SUPERScriptBold\">&reg;</SUP><B CLASS=\"Bold\"> DISPOSABLE SYRINGE</B></P>\n<P CLASS=\"Body\">The syringe is designed to provide the choice of either insertion of the full cannula as has traditionally been practiced, or insertion of no more than 1/8 inch of the cannula, as reported by Eberhart, R.J., et. al. 1987. Current Concepts of Bovine Mastitis, 3rd Edition, National Mastitis Council, Arlington, VA.</P>\n<P CLASS=\"Num1\"><B CLASS=\"Bold\">a.\tFull insertion: </B>Remove the red end cap by pulling straight up as shown. Gently insert the full cannula into the teat canal; carefully infuse the product.</P>\n<P CLASS=\"Num1\"><B CLASS=\"Bold\">b.\tPartial insertion: </B>Remove the red end cap by pulling straight up as shown. border=\"0\">\n<P CLASS=\"Label\"><B CLASS=\"Bold\">ADMINISTRATION</B></P>\n<P CLASS=\"Body\"><B CLASS=\"Bold\">Treatment: </B>Wash teats thoroughly with warm water containing a suitable dairy antiseptic. Dry teats thoroughly. Milk out udder completely. Using an alcohol pad provided, wipe off the end of the affected teat using a separate pad for each teat. Choose the desired insertion length (full or partial) and insert tip into teat canal; push plunger to dispense entire contents, massage the quarter to distribute the suspension into the milk cistern.</P>\n<P CLASS=\"Label\"><B CLASS=\"Bold\">CONTRAINDICATIONS</B></P>\n<P CLASS=\"Body\">As with all drugs, the use of <B CLASS=\"Bold\">SPECTRAMAST</B><SUP CLASS=\"SUPERScriptBold\">&reg;</SUP><B CLASS=\"Bold\"> LC </B>Sterile Suspension is contraindicated in animals previously found to be hypersensitive to the drug.</P>\n<P CLASS=\"Body\"><B CLASS=\"Bold\">Discard Empty Container: DO NOT REUSE</B></P>\n<P CLASS=\"Body\"><B CLASS=\"Bold\">KEEP OUT OF REACH OF CHILDREN</B></P>\n<P CLASS=\"Label\"><B CLASS=\"Bold\">WARNINGS</B></P>\n<P CLASS=\"Body\">Penicillins and cephalosporins can cause allergic reactions in sensitized individuals. Topical exposures to such antimicrobials, including ceftiofur, may elicit mild to severe allergic reactions in some individuals. Repeated or prolonged exposure may lead to sensitization. Avoid direct contact of the product with the skin, eyes, mouth and clothing. Sensitization</P>\n<P CLASS=\"Body\">of the skin may be avoided by wearing protective gloves.</P>\n<P CLASS=\"Body\">Persons with a known hypersensitivity to penicillin or cephalosporins should avoid exposure to this product.</P>\n<P CLASS=\"Body\">In case of accidental eye exposure, flush with water for 15 minutes. In case of accidental skin exposure, wash with soap and water. Remove contaminated clothing. If allergic reaction occurs (e.g., skin rash, hives, difficult breathing), seek medical attention.</P>\n<P CLASS=\"Body\">The safety data sheet contains more detailed occupational safety information. To report suspected adverse events, for technical assistance or to obtain a copy of the safety data sheet (SDS), contact Zoetis Inc. at 1-888-963-8471. For additional information about adverse drug experience reporting for animal drugs, contact FDA at 1-888-FDA-VETS or online at http://www.fda.gov/AnimalVeterinary/SafetyHealth.</P>\n<P obtained during treatment and during the milk discard period should be properly discarded and not fed to calves. SPECTRAMAST LC is intended for use in lactating dairy cattle with mastitis associated only with the specified labeled pathogens. To assure responsible antimicrobial drug use, it is expected that subclinical mastitis will be diagnosed using a positive culture or other pathogen-specific test in addition to any other appropriate veterinary medical evaluation prior to treatment. Cows with systemic clinical signs caused by mastitis should receive other appropriate therapy under the direction of a licensed veterinarian. After successful treatment, reinfection may occur unless good herd management, sanitation, and mechanical safety measures are practiced. Affected cows should be watched carefully to detect recurrence of infection and possible spread to other animals.</P>\n<P CLASS=\"Label\"><B CLASS=\"Bold\">CLINICAL MICROBIOLOGY:</B></P>\n<P CLASS=\"BodyKwn\">Ceftiofur is a broad-spectrum cephalosporin antibiotic that exerts its effect by inhibiting bacterial cell wall synthesis. Like other &beta;-lactam antimicrobial agents, cephalosporins inhibit cell wall synthesis by interfering with the enzymes essential for peptidoglycan synthesis. This effect results in lysis of the bacterial cell and accounts for the bactericidal nature of these agents. Ceftiofur has demonstrated <EM CLASS=\"Italics\">in vitro</EM> activity against coagulase-negative staphylococci, <EM CLASS=\"Italics\">Streptococcus dysgalactiae</EM>, and <EM CLASS=\"Italics\">Escherichia coli</EM>. The minimum inhibitory concentrations (MICs) of ceftiofur against indicated pathogens collected from field studies conducted in 2000 were determined using methods recommended by the National Committee for Clinical Laboratory Standards (NCCLS, M31-A) and are represented in Table 1, below:</P>\n<P CLASS=\"BodyKwn\"><B CLASS=\"Bold\">Table 1. Ceftiofur Minimum Inhibitory Concentrations (MIC) Values* of Isolates from Field Studies Evaluating Clinical Mastitis in Dairy Cows in the U.S. During 2000</B></P>\n<table susceptibility data and clinical effectiveness is unknown.</P>\n<P CLASS=\"Body\">** The lowest MIC to encompass 90% of the most susceptible isolates.</P>\n<P CLASS=\"Label\"><B CLASS=\"Bold\">EFFECTIVENESS</B></P>\n<P CLASS=\"Body\">In 1999 to 2000, the efficacy of ceftiofur was demonstrated in a pivotal multi-location field trial in lactating dairy cattle with clinical mastitis in one quarter. Ceftiofur was formulated in stable cottonseed oil sterile suspension manufactured under GMP guidelines. Cows with mastitis were enrolled in the study if visually abnormal milk (clots, flakes, or watery secretion) or if udder swelling, heat, pain or redness were present and the milk was not yet visually abnormal but California Mastitis Test (CMT) gave results of 2 or greater. A total of 13 trial sites enrolled 352 cows in the study. Cows were assigned to one of three treatment groups: non-treated control, 62.5 mg ceftiofur, and 125 mg ceftiofur. Each treatment group received an intramammary infusion twice at a 24-hour interval in the affected quarter. The non-treated controls received no therapy. Three different definitions for cure were used for analysis purposes: 1)&nbsp;a clinical cure was defined as the milk and udder returning to normal 14 days after the last treatment and remaining normal at the 21 day time point; 2)&nbsp;a bacterial cure was defined as the absence of the pre-treatment pathogen at 14 and 21&nbsp;days post-treatment; 3)&nbsp;a protocol cure was defined as the absence of the pre-treatment pathogen at 14 and 21 days post-treatment and return to normal of the milk and udder 14 days after the last treatment and remaining normal at the 21 day time point. Three hundred and thirty seven cows were analyzed for clinical cure rates, which were 54.7% (64/117) for the non-treated control group compared to 69.4% (75/108) for the 62.5 mg treatment group and 78.6% (88/112) for the 125 mg treatment group. The 125 mg treatment group&rsquo;s clinical cure rate was significantly greater than the non-treated control (P=0.002). One hundred and forty six cows were analyzed for bacterial cure rates, which were 41.3% (19/46) for the non-treated control group, 45.6% (21/46) for the 62.5 mg treatment group and 70.4% (38/54) for the 125&nbsp;mg treatment group. The 125 mg treatment group&rsquo;s bacterial cure rate was significantly greater than the non-treated control group (P=0.006). One hundred and forty six cows were analyzed for protocol cure rates, which were 63.0% (34/54) for the 125 mg treatment group, 41.3% (19/46) for the 62.5 mg treatment group and 23.9% (11/46) for the non-treated control group. The 125 mg treatment group&rsquo;s protocol cure rate was significantly better than the non-treated control (P&lt;0.001) for treatment of clinical mastitis. Thus, 125 mg of ceftiofur administered via intramammary infusion twice at a 24-hour interval was effective in the treatment of clinical mastitis in lactating dairy cows associated with coagulase-negative staphylococci, (CNS), <EM CLASS=\"Italics\">Streptococcus dysgalactiae</EM>, and <EM CLASS=\"Italics\">Escherichia coli</EM>.</P>\n<P CLASS=\"Body\">The effectiveness of ceftiofur for the treatment of subclinical mastitis was demonstrated in a 10-site field study in lactating dairy cattle in 2013. Cows with subclinical mastitis were enrolled in the study if milk and udders were visually normal, composite quantitative somatic cell count (SCC) was &gt;400,000 cells/mL, and milk culture was positive for a mastitis-causing pathogen. Cows were assigned to one of two treatment groups: SPECTRAMAST LC (125&nbsp;mg ceftiofur equivalents per dose) or an equivalent volume of saline. Each treatment group received an intramammary infusion twice at a 24-hour interval in the affected quarter. Treatment success (bacterial cure) was defined as the absence of the pre-treatment pathogen at 14 and 20 days post-treatment. Three hundred thirty-six cows were analyzed for bacterial cure rates. There was a statistically significantly different (P&nbsp;&lt;&nbsp;0.0001) overall proportion of treatment successes in the SPECTRAMAST LC-treated group (44%, 75/164) compared with the saline-treated group (4%, 8/172). Additionally, a clinically-relevant ratio of clinical successes to failures was observed in the SPECTRAMAST LC-treated group compared to the saline-treated group for evaluable cases of subclinical mastitis associated with CNS and with <EM CLASS=\"Italics\">S. dysgalactiae</EM>.</P>\n<P CLASS=\"Label\"><B CLASS=\"Bold\">ANIMAL SAFETY</B></P>\n<P CLASS=\"Body\">A pivotal GLP udder irritation study was conducted in 40 cows to assess udder irritation following daily intramammary infusion of an oil.based suspension containing 125&nbsp;mg of ceftiofur for up to 8 consecutive days. A transient and clinically insignificant rise in SCC to levels &lt;200,000 cell/mL was observed following infusion in normal cows with very low pre-infusion SCC (&lt;10,000 cell/mL). This elevation is not unexpected with oil-based suspensions. The duration of therapy did not affect this elevation. No udder clinical signs of irritation (swelling, pain,"}

Iteration: 1 - recall or decline a prescription
Request Description
Prescriptions are immutable except for metadata, and cannot actually be deleted. This endpoint makes a prescription unavailable for use. If called by the VOR, it sets staus to RECALLED. If called by the MOR to whom it is prescribed, it sets status to DECLINED. New cases cannot be enrolled if either RECALLED or DECLIENED.
